description.text:
Like any good engineer should I often look at my tools and ask myself â€œHow could this be more awesome AND more dangerous at the same time?â€
The obvious answer when looking at a Dremel was â€œadd a propeller.â€  This work is inspired by, but not derived from, the [now defunct?] Prop Rocket thing by James.  Iâ€™m the wrong sort of engineer to design a propeller with any sort of real efficiency but itâ€™s my hope that this will make some one more knowledgeable give some tips or upload their own design.  Since Iâ€™ve now lost a few of these out my window, I guess itâ€™s reached â€œflies well enoughâ€ status.
I showed this to a friend who requested a clarifications.  This is a variation on those old toys which had a separate propeller press fit on to some type of handle.  When the propeller is spinning fast enough the lift it provides over comes the friction fit that holds it down.  At that point the propeller pops off and flies away.  This is a version of that spun by a Dremel.  It is not intended to fly away with your Dremel.
Warning: This is not intended to be a toy or even really be safe to use.  Donâ€™t attempt to use this unless youâ€™re sure of your capabilities (are you certain your single walled print can hold blades together at Dremel speeds?).  Even then I take no responsibility for you making one.

It's hard to print in my experience.  I experimented with easier to print blade designs but nothing flew close to as well as this.  I used full supports in skeinforge, which just added a little raft under the blades, and put my print head a bit lower then normal.  
This is sized to it fit over the small sanding wheel Dremel attachment.  It should fit on tight enough that it wonâ€™t pop off until an appropriate spin speed is reached.  I suggest wrapping the attachment in tape or sanding down the inside of the hub as needed.
You will want it to stick to the top of the sanding wheel harder then you may expect.  For best flight it will need to stay on all the way up to full speed and be able to release with a slight shake.  The internal hub diameter is 15mm and my sanding wheel was 15.2mm.  You may need to resize.  The first time I fit each new one on I do so with the sanding wheel spinning slowly.
Make sure you and everyone else clear the stupid space before spinning it up.  When Iâ€™ve been test flying these Iâ€™ve either been standing behind a glass door or window with my gloved handed holding the Dremel on the other side.  I did one test flight inside and it hit the ceiling at an angle hard enough that it shattered.
Use at your own risk.

title: Identifying Animals by Tracks and Scat

description.text: 3D Printed tracks and scat are used to identify animals found in the wild. Often students can not be taken outside to track animals, so the animal tracks can be printed and brought inside.

Printer Brand:

0,2mm

Notes:

Rafts are probably not needed, but I use them anyway.

The tracks were made using a life-size drawing of a deer print. I then converted the 2D picture into an .svg file and uploaded it into Tinkercad. I then used the .svg as a hole in a base that I made to mimic a print.

The scat was made by creating a few different shapes in Sculptris and then printing out a number of each design.

Our school teaches a forestry class. Students study the animals found in local forests. When they get to the orienteering section of the course, they will be asked to find evidence of wildlife near the school. If they cannot leave the school, or if there is no evidence to be found in our area, then creating artificial evidence is a good way to introduce students to wildlife they may encounter. Objectives
Students will gain an understanding of how to recognize wildlife in their surroundings by studying the evidence left behind. Skills
Students will:
  • Use a variety of methods to observe, collect, document, classify, and summarize data on animal tracks.
  • Use a field guide and related references to identify and interpret wildlife tracks.
  • Recognize animals that live in the local community.
  • Analyze data to construct a reasonable explanation for a wild animal’s behavior, traits, and needs.

Option 1: Students are given information about finding animal tracks in the wild and use that information to create a 3D model of the animal tracks for a class library of tracks. this can be done by sketching and scanning a life-size print, or finding a simple print online and converting it to an .svg file. Then use a program like Tinkercad to create the print. The .svg file would be imported and used as a hole in a thin solid base. The scat is more of a freeform design, so the Sculptris software would be a better choice for that. Option 2: Instructor designs and prints tracks and scat ahead of time and has a classroom gallery of wildlife evidence. Students are given an animal track guide (see files), and are asked to identify the animal that would have created the track. Then they will match the animal track with the scat that would be left behind by that animal. If possible, student can be taken outside to search for clues of animal activity around the school. The printed tracks would be kept as a class library for reference. Once students know what they are looking for, they can follow the lesson located here: https://nationalzoo.si.edu/education/classroomscience/animaltracks/teacher/default.cfm to bait areas around the school to see what sort of wildlife is attracted to your area. The formative assessment would be the completed worksheets.
Copies of student worksheets (found in "files")
90-minute class

One option for this lesson is to have students learn about animal tracks and scat by designing the printed tracks.  If the students will not be doing this, then the instructor will need to have as many different local animal tracks and scat samples as possible for the students to use as a guide.

Yes. Thats correct. However I still find ABS to be the better material for such application like mounts, hook, hinges etc.

title: Canning Funnel for Pint or Half Pint Wide Mouth Ball or Mason Jar

description.text: About this time of the year I make and can my own cranberry/cherry compote. I didn't have a canning funnel so I tried a similar Thingiverse funnel but it was either for a different jar or scaled wrong for standard wide mouth ball/mason jars. I designed a new one for proper fit.

The funnel was redesigned in Solidworks  2013 then printed on an Ordbot Hadron Printer in ABS with a modified QU-BD stepstruder. It was printed using a 1.75 mm ABS filament with a layer thickness of .2 mm (200 microns) and an 85% fill factor with scaffolding support on.   
After various experiments I settled on a wall thickness of .060 in thickness (1.5mm) as a good balance between sturdiness and the amount of the filament used.  A thin wash of Acetone will seal the surfaces nicely.  
ABS Printing was performed at 235C on clear Monokote film over a heated glass bed at 110C for the first layer and 100C for all subsequent layers.  Aquanet Extra Super Hold was sprayed on the Monokote to insure stick down.  I've had no ABS stick down issues since I began using the above technique.

description.text: I was tired of adjusting my extruder idler block for proper tension. I think that it would be much easier to adjust tension if I have an easy-grip nut cap. So here it is!

This one is done in OpenSCAD. I spent a few minutes more to make it parametric. So now you can choose nut size, grip type (none, wing, rib) and presence of support structure (a little cross-like thing in the middle) which makes 3D prints more nice and is easy to remove. In OpenSCAD just use the wingnut(m, grip, support) module. Parameters are:
m - nut size (metric)
grip - grip type: 0=none, 1=wings, 2=ribs
support - presence of support structure wingnut(4, 1, true); will generate M4 cap with wings and support,
wingnut(5, 2, false); will generate M5 cap with ribs, but no support,
wingnut(10, 0, true); will generate round M10 cap with support.

description.text:
CVC (Consonant Vowel Consonant) Word plates are good for both guided and independent work by preschool and Kindergarten students.

Using big curve, little curve, long line, short line, students form the letters that make up the CVC words on the plates.

Additional CVC word plates may be designed using the Letter and Word Formation Plates listed on another Thingiverse listing (http://www.thingiverse.com/thing:1746697) depending on the size of your 3D printer print area.

When printing on a single extruder machine, the plates can be made more interesting by pausing and performing a filament change once the base layer has been made. For letters with crossing elements, 4 switches of filament colors with 2 for each stick layer, create an evn more colorful and intuitive letter formation plate.

(The picture of BIN has imperfections due to extruder issues unrelated to this project. A new printout and picture will be uploaded soon.)

description.header: Project: CVC Plate Word and Letter Formation
description.text:
CVC Plate Word and Letter Formation

Preschool and Kindergarten students learning letter formation and practicing handwriting will find the CVC Plate Word and Letter Formation as a useful supplement.

Educators covering CVC word spelling with Kindergarten, 1st Grade and 2nd Grade intervention may also use the plates as an engaging kinesthetic way for students to practice spelling at the same time.

Overview & Background

Educators will find ideas here for enhancing letter formation instruction through fun kinesthetic learning that allows for both guided teacher-led activities as well as independent work for accelerated students. CVC Word and Letter Formation plates are also good choice time options.

Using the Letter Formation Plates in Thingiverse (URL HERE), educators can build upon these CVC Word Plate examples and 3D model more CVC words for students to practice that are on the languages arts curriculum in use.

Objectives

Students will learn how to spell CVC words by building the words not just from letters but from the component short lines, long lines, large curves and small curves.

While spelling CVC words, students are practicing letter formation.

Audiences

CVC Plate Word and Letter Formation Plates are primarily for preschool and Kindergarten.

Subjects

English Language Arts

Skills Learned (Standards)

CCSS.ELA-LITERACY.RF.K.1.B
Recognize that spoken words are represented in written language by specific sequences of letters.

CCSS.ELA-LITERACY.RF.K.1.D
Recognize and name all upper- and lowercase letters of the alphabet.

CCSS.ELA-LITERACY.RF.K.2.D
Isolate and pronounce the initial, medial vowel, and final sounds (phonemes) in three-phoneme (consonant-vowel-consonant, or CVC) words.1 (This does not include CVCs ending with /l/, /r/, or /x/.)

CCSS.ELA-LITERACY.RF.K.3.C
Read common high-frequency words by sight (e.g., the, of, to, you, she, my, is, are, do, does).

Lesson/Activity

Duration:
CVC Word and Letter Formation Plates can be integrated into current language arts curriculum as a kinesthetic activity or as an independent learning activity. It can range from 1-30 minutes depending on the number of plates created.

Preparation:
Educator 3D prints the standard little line, big line, little curve and big curve. Educator then prints example CVC word plates or using Thingiverse project (http://www.thingiverse.com/thing:1746697), 3D models new CVC words matching current curriculum and prints those.

References

The CVC Word and Letter Formation Plates are easy for educators to use without much work. Refer to current curriculum for ideas of specific word lists from CVC study or sight words to build more plates.

Rubric & Assessment

When students have completed building a plate, they can either show it to the teacher. If the classroom is mobile-enabled, students can take a picture to upload to their portfolio.

Handouts & Assets

Handouts would be the Language Arts curriculum being used by the educator that match the CVC words being practiced.

title: E3D Bowden Makerbot Replicator 2X Conversion Bracket

description.text:
I haven't been using my Replicator 2X for a while now, mainly because it doesn't extrude well...or at all most times. I decided to swap over to a Bowden style extruder.

I originally followed the guide here. The guide gave a link to some 3d printed parts, they were all undersize for me and I didn't like the way the hot end was being secured...so I made my own.

Note: I never really use the dual extruder setup, so this bracket only supports one extruder.

Bowden Parts:

  • 24V 1.75mm Bowden Hot End Kit
  • EZStruder Cold End Kit

IMPORTANT: On the EZStruder Cold End Kit, you need to check the 4mm Quick Connect Fitting!!! I forgot to do this...

Other Parts (I used 4-40 instead of M3...but they're essentially the same size):

  • 4 - M3 x 18mm Bolts (Hot end)
  • 2 - M3 Nuts (Hot end)
  • 2 - M3 Lock Nuts (Hot end - I didn't use these...you should...)
  • 1 - 1/4 x 4in Aluminum Rod (Hot end)
  • 2 - M3 x 35mm Bolts (Cold end - You could use all 4 of the stepper holes...I did not)
  • 2 - M3 Washers (Cold end - You could use all 4 of the stepper holes...I did not)

Instructions (I followed the original guide for the majority of this...but in summary):

  1. Print parts.
  2. Disassemble Makerbot hot end (remove B wires, keep A).
  3. Assemble Bowden hot end (use the Makerbot thermocouple).
  4. Assemble EZStruder kit.
  5. Drill 2 holes in the back of the printer (I just eye-balled them...).
  6. Unscrew 2 diagonal stepper motor bolts (you could use all 4, if so drill 4 holes).
  7. Insert the 35mm bolts with washers into the stepper motor on the back.
  8. Load, level, and print (be sure to move your bed down a bit to make sure you don't gouge it!).

Finishing Note: On the first hot end picture, you will see 2 black bolts where the limit switch foot is. I lowered the head a bit, and failed to compensate for the lowering of the foot...thus the limit switch wasn't hit by it. This is fixed in the uploaded design, AND YOU DO NOT NEED THEM.

description.text:

description.text:
I built schlem's 3D printer enclosure (having long since been banished to the most remote corner of my garage by she-who... you know...).  
I found that the door sagged by about 3/4 inch, so I created this simple support bracket. I glued it onto the outside of the door using cyanoacrylate (superglue). As with all my cyanoacrylate on acrylic, I needed to clamp it while drying (using spring clamps).  
Some of the acrylic I used was 0.100 inch instead of the 0.080 inch thickness, and this may have caused the door sag.  
I am using this with my Prusa i3 from MakerFarm. The only change I made to schlem's plans was to put the filament ingress on the top, but that was mostly a matter of preference. I've included only the door hanger STL and FreeCAD source rather than create yet another copy - see schlem's original and link to instructables for complete instructions and all other needed parts.

I chose to try using cyanoacrylate (super glue). I used one of the gel variants (which differs from normal cyanoacrylate only in that it stays in place on vertical surfaces a little better).  
I did this mostly to avoid having to mix batch after batch of two-part epoxy.  
It worked rather well but I needed to keep things in place for about 90 seconds with firm pressure when gluing ABS pieces against smooth acrylic. Spring clamps were very helpful for the pieces where spring clamps could reach. When I needed to glue ABS to ABS, it "grabbed" within a few seconds (as you might normally expect with superglue). The same is true of skin, so when holding pieces in place be careful!  
Another important point to add to the build instructions (as noted by other commenters) is to first use your hole saw to drill out 1 inch and 2 inch holes in a piece of 1/2 inch plywood and use this as a hole saw guide (for cutting holes in acrylic without the center bit in the hole saw, which normally stabilizes it). Clamping the acrylic between this hole saw guide and another piece of plywood (or particle board) allowed me to make fairly clean crack-free holes.

This is an experimental piece, mostly a design challenge to myself to work on techniques for making complex snap-together multi-part models.  
The goals of the design were as follows:  
Game-accurate color with all colors due to the intrinsic color of the plastic and no painting required.  
No directional bias in the assembled piece, such as you see with all-one-piece cubes with different finish on the sides versus top due to the nature of the print process.  This means each corner, edge, and face piece is indivudually printed flat on the bed.  
No unavoidable seams.  The only seams between pieces are at borders between one color and another.  
All snap-together, with no glue required.  Revised version posted now really holds together well.  
As a result of these goals this is a fairly complex print, with 40 parts that need to be snapped together in a specific order.  
This Companion Cube is separated into parts for each color - white, grey, and pink - as well as separate parts for each corner, edge, and face.  There are 5 different shapes, and a total of 40 parts which need to be printed.  
It should hold together securely without needing glue, although you can use glue when assembling it if you wish.  You may also print in white or clear and then paint all the parts if you don't have the appropriate colors.  
Completely revised design posted 11/7 - revised many parts to eliminate weak spots and make it hold together with no glue.

Print 6 each of the white and the pink face pieces.
Print 8 each of the grey and the white corner pieces.
Print 12 each of the white edge pieces. Clean up any stray strings, drooping bits, etc. The inside of the grey corner pieces and the white face pieces especially need to be free of blobs and strings. Press one white face piece onto each pink face piece. Depending on your printer you may have to shave the inside of the heart outline on the white piece to get this to snap together cleanly. The four white tabs are kind of fragile and may break, but they don't matter much and you can lose one or two of them and still have the white and pink pieces hold together snugly. Press one white corner piece through each grey corner piece. If you have no strings or blobs they should fit snugly together. Take two of the corner assemblies and join them together with an edge piece. The tabs on the white edge pieces snap into the sockets on the white corner pieces, and hold the grey corner pieces in place as they do. Repeat this step three more times, so you have four joined corner pairs. Take two corner pairs, one face assembly, and two edge pieces. Use the edge pieces to join the two corner pair assemblies together into a face, with the face assembly sandwiched between them. Do this one more time with the other two corner pairs. Finally take the remaining four face assemblies and edge pieces and use them to join the two assemblies from the previous step together. This step is a bit tricky as it requires you to push the four edge pins into one of the assemblies with the four face pieces sandwiched between them. I found that the easiest way to do this is to push the edge pieces in partway, tilted out away from the center slightly. You can then insert the face pieces between them, and then push each edge in the rest of the way, making sure the pink tabs on the face pieces fit into the small slot in the center of each edge piece. You can then push the other assembly from the previous place onto the open side of the pins and snap the entire thing together.

Adobe Illustrator script that generates OpenScad source to create stamps.

I need to label all my sons clothes for his kindergarten. Including socks!! Using stick on labels was not an option as it would most likely cause discomfort.

So I had to find a better way: stamps!

Inspired by an article in makezine.com that shows how to create stamps with openscad I
converted this script, which is a modified version of this script

I used fabric paint which is fixed using heat after drying, but any other paint would work for other materials. Simple "airy" letters work best!

Note:
Tested only under OSX with AI CS 2015. Script added to "/Applications/Adobe Illustrator CC 2015/Presets.localized/en_US/Scripts" ['en_US' can be different under other localisation]

(Files "sample.stl" and "sound.stl" can be ignored)

Update 27/08/2016:

  • removed generation options from Adobe and now those are only available under the source OpenSCAD. Default values will be used and the user will have to change them manually. This allows to more flexibility.
  • added border and round base, both configurable in the OpenSCAD source. Set border to 0 or negative to remove it, set round_base = false to get a rectangular base. Round base works best for very short words - even better for chinese characters.
  • added checkbox to allow automatic opening of the generated file in OpenSCAD

title: No Man's Sky - Grave Marker USB Necklace
license: Creative Commons - Attribution - Non-Commercial - Share Alike

description.text:
This is a very simplified model of a Grave Marker, an object found in the PS4/PC game, No Man's Sky.

Upon your death, the location is marked with this giant hovering diamond. At the center of that diamond is a sphere that contains your inventory.
Now you can have your own! It's a necklace -- and the container core is a removable USB flash drive! Carry your stuff on you or just wear the empty grave. Do what you want.

Assembly video further down this page.

Printer:

FlashForge Finder

Rafts:

Yes

Supports:

Yes

Resolution:

100 Micron

Infill:

15%

Notes:

This Thing requires a lot more complicated parts then I had hoped, I apologize.
Supports and rafting will be necessary, especially since we're using such small fiddly bits. Some basic cleanup will also be necessary, especially around the holes for the string.

Assembly Video. Flash drive used: http://amzn.to/2bIxCiJ Non-3D Printed Things Needed!

Outside of the parts you've printed here, you will need the following:

  1. String/twine/cord for the necklace.
  2. Superglue or some other appropriate adhesive.
  3. Compact/Low Profile flash drive. These are flash drives that are the same dimensions as the USB port itself. Just place the drive in and glue it in place with the two hemispheres.

If you don't want to use glue, I did include specific mounting blocks for the SiliconPower "Jewel" flash drive, as that is the one I had on hand. I recommend this one as it's easiest to mount because of the openings in the metal. Found here: http://amzn.to/2bIxCiJ

It does also work with a Patriot S-Mini flash drive, although you will have to remove the silicon body and use glue. Found here: http://amzn.to/2bQtPy2

How!?

I used screenshots I took myself as reference to recreate the object in Tinkercad. Or, at least as best I could. It's quite complex with a lot of details ingame. So I simplified it. After I created the object, I brainstormed ways to disassemble and reassemble it. With a plan in mind, I started bisecting it and complicating it.
Even though it may seem simpler than the Knowledge Stone, this was far more complicated to try to make "work". Took me several revisions before I was happy with the assembly and outcome. It utilizes more parts than I'd like, but it's the best I can do for now.

I have a version in the works that isn't a necklace, just the object, and it will have minimal seamlines, and require you assemble the core around a red glass marble. For those of you who want a more accurate prop as opposed to fancy jewelry.

This is hard work, guys.

Gosh.

description.text:
If you, like me, have a garage or other place where WiFi reception is poor because you are to far away from your acces point or modem, then this directional BiQuad WiFi antenna might come handy. With this antenna you can increase the working distance of your WiFi by up to many hundreds of meters.

All you need are:
Copper electrical wire (1.5mm squared, or 1.33 diameter in millimeters)
An antenna base connector (I used a BNC here, but "N" is better)
Some metal reflector where you can solder on
My 3D printed mold.

The costs of this project are only a few dollars or Euro's.

Look at the video for the build of this antenna:
https://youtu.be/DToyFX81tm0

Printer:

Da Vinci Pro

Rafts:

No

Supports:

No

Resolution:

0.2

Infill:

15%

How you make it

Start by straighten the copper wire and make a 90 degrees angle. Now bend the wire in the mold using pliers and make sure the wire never touches itself by insulating the pieces where it touches.

Watch the video to see how to bend the wire in the printed mold. You can leave the wire in because you use the mold to keep the antenna on the right distance.

Use a metal (copper or tin) plate of about 25x18cm in size. In the middle of the plate you drill a hole of the size of the connector you are using. Place the connector in this hole and tighten it.

Now place the antenna on the connector and solder the 2 wires coming from it to the ground of the connector and the metal plate. Solder the live end to the part of the antenna I point out in the video.

Now you got yourself a perfect WiFi antenna to be used on a WiFi card or USB WiFi dongle with a antenna connector.

123D Design

The antenna is draw in 123Ddesign to make sure I have all the correct measurements and because the cable is inserted in the printed mold, you can not make a mistake with the length of the copper wire.

The frequency where the antenna is 1:1 is at channel 6 of the WiFi spectrum.

description.text:
This is the second version of a tripod designed for the iPhone SE with an Apple leather case. However, just like version one, it works with almost any phone. As long as the phone is less then 10 mm thick and the width doesn't exceed 10 cm (which would be a huge phone...) you should be fine. An animation of the features can be found here: https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=F9A_9K1HN2U.

First version: http://www.thingiverse.com/thing:1641415

The second version came to be because of two main reasons: Firstly the original tripod was way to weak. Secondly, you needed a screwdriver to adjust it. After initial assembly, this tripod won't require any tools to be operated.

Depending on the tolerances of your printer the threads might not be perfect. This model is designed with a tolerance of 1 mm. However, if you would like a file with another tolerance, post a comment and i'll make it happen!

Printer:

Velleman Vertex K8400

Rafts:

Doesn't Matter

Supports:

Yes

Resolution:

Preferably 0.1 mm for the parts with threads, for the remaining parts it doesn't matter, I printed them at 0,2 mm.

Infill:

Something between 10%-15% should be sufficient. For extra durability you might wan't to print the screw at 20%.

Notes:

In order to make assembling easier it's recommended that the parts which will be threaded by metal threads are printed in a soft material, in my case ABS. This means that the following parts should be ABS:

  • Feet
  • LegMount
  • Thumbscrew

The remaining parts can be printed with PLA.

The threads are designed for a printer with 1 mm tolerance. If you would like a file with another value, post a comment and I will make that happen!

Required hardware

The assembly requires:

  • Three 10 cm parts of M8 threaded rod
  • Four 25 mm M3 screws
  • Four hexagonal M3 nuts
Required printed parts

To get a complete tripod you need to print:

  • One HolderBottom (PLA)
  • One HolderTop (PLA)
  • One Screw (PLA)
  • One MountingPlate (PLA)
  • Three LegMount (ABS)
  • Three Feet (ABS)
  • Four Thumbscrew (ABS)

The materials specified are just recommendations and I'm sure it's possible to use other materials. However these were the one I used.

Assembly
  1. In order to keep the M3-screws in place they need a hexagonal head. Since I could find such screws I combined a screw and a nut. Tighten the nut all the way up to the screws head and fasten it with superglue (see picture below). Make four of these.
  2. Create threads in the thumbscrews by inserting the M3-screws. If the holes are to small you can enlarge them with a drill bit that slightly smaller then the screw. After threading, if there to much friction in the thread you can wear it down be repeatedly inserting and removing the screw using a drill.
  3. Assemble the legs by threading the threaded rod into both the feet and the leg mounts using the same procedure as above.
  4. Assemble the rest of the tripod according to the pictures above. Remember that the printed screw is both left- and right-threaded, therefore make sure the orientation is correct when inserting it into the top and bottom holder.
See step one in Assembly
The model was designed using Autodesk Inventor 2016.

Let me begin with - I teach math - please don't judge me.

My plan was to design something in clay and then try to recreate it in modelling software. I apparently can't work in clay. So this design was made using Sculptris design software. Since I am a pre-novice with this software, my sculpture is more abstract than I would have liked. I wanted to import it into other software, but the detail of the part was so great that no other software would accept it, so I just saved it as an .obj file and brought it into Makerbot Desktop to print. I then tried to recreate it in clay and we can see how that turned out. Again...math teacher...
NGSS CCSS

Online Sculpting Art is becoming a high tech field. Many forms of art are now created on computers, when they were once done by hand. This lesson takes the tactile lesson of sculpture, and transforms it into a technology art form. Skills Learned Students will choose from a range of materials and methods of traditional and contemporary artistic practices, following or breaking established conventions, to plan the making of multiple works of art and design based on a theme, idea, or concept. Through experimentation, practice, and persistence, students will demonstrate acquisition of skills and knowledge in a chosen art form.

Phase 1 Phase one of this project is for the student to create a clay sculpture based on criteria set forth by the teacher depending on the level of the students. Since my level is novice, I made a simplistic model of a person. Those with better skills and better tools should be held to a much higher standard. The reason for this phase is that students tend to get online and just get lost in the 3D design. Having them create a solid model first lets the instructor know that they will be focused when they get into the software. Minor adjustments could be allowed, but students must recreate their clay sculpture in the software. Phase 2 Phase two of this project is where the students take their clay sculpture and recreate it in the design software. If a 3D scanner is available, this may also be used to import the structure into the software. I have no experience with this, but I hear it is wonderful. Phase 3 Phase three is printing out the digital copy of the sculpture and comparing it to the original.

description.text: 3D printing is finding its way into our business classes and instructors are at a loss to know what to do with them. This lesson is my attempt to put together a lesson for our business classes that would include 3D printing.

Printer Brand:

MakerBot

Printer:

MakerBot Replicator (5th Generation)

Rafts:

Yes

Supports:

No

Notes:

Part of this lesson is to figure the cost vs benefit of a higher resolution and infill.

Using Tinkercad, I created the keychain with a simple cylinder and a tube. I then imported an .svg of a polar bear inside a paw and attempted to print it. I did not like the way it turned out, so I eventually settled on just the paw. The .svg used it attached.

Our local schools have added 3D printers in their business computer labs, but did not tell the teachers how they were supposed to be used. This lesson is one that can be incorporated into a cost/benefit analysis lesson or an entrepreneurial lesson. Students will be designing a widget (in this case I designed a marketable school key-chain with the school logo). Students will then determine whether the product is marketable and at what price. They will take into account the time and cost of printing and the various options of printer settings. Compute the cost of production for a given business venture Distinguish between fixed and variable costs of production and give examples of each Compare revenue and cost data to determine profitability of an entrepreneurial venture Create a product and price it for profitability. Skills
  • Develop a management plan for an entrepreneurial venture
  • Develop a business plan
  • Analyze customer groups and develop a plan to identify, reach, and keep customers in a specific target market.
    • Duration
    This is a project-based lesson that can be a semester project depending on how far the instructor wants to take it. Part one: Students learn about creating and marketing a product for sale. They need to understand costs vs benefits of their product and determine marketability. Part two: Students will design a product using 3D design software (I used Tinkercad) and determine the cost of producing this product. Part three (optional): Students print out their products and attempt to sell them.

Students need to have a background in product development, so if they do not, some time should be spent discussing what goes into bringing a new product to market.
Students will then be tasked with coming up with a product that they could possibly sell. They will be working in teams to brainstorm a product idea, then do some market research to determine whether it is salable. The best idea to keep students engaged would be to determine if their peers would buy their product, and how much they would be willing to pay for it.
Next comes the design process. I went through several iterations of my key-chain design (see pictures), After the product is designed on paper, it needs to be designed using 3D design software (I used Tinkercad). Things to consider in the design: Will it need supports? How many will fit on a printer and any one time? How much filament is going to be required for this design? How long will it take to print? I designed my key-chain and then got all these answers from previewing it in Makerbot Desktop software. My keychain printed with default setting (using a raft) would take 11.28g of filament. At $0.053/g for standard filament, that gives us a cost of $0.60 and 1hr8min for each print. Without the raft, I was able to lower that to 7.99g of filament at a cost of $0.42 and 1hr to print. With the limitations of my machine (and by limitations, I mean my ability to use it - I am sure that it could do much more, but I need to work with it some more), I was able to print 6 key-chains in 6 hours overnight. Students would have to develop their own cost analysis and then determine what the actual cost would be (including design and time printing) and price their product accordingly. The culmination of the project would be having the students print out their product and market it to their peers. The marketing campaign would be a completely separate lesson. Any profits could be used to resupply filament or take a field trip.

Students will be designing their product using 3D software, so each student group would require computer access and software accounts.
3D printer with filament
Students will be graded on the completeness and reasonableness of their business plan.  They will then have a separate grade for their design and marketing campaign.

description.text: This lesson challenges the students to design and build a musical instrument that will make at least three different pitches and to create a song to play on it.

Two of the instruments shown are just examples of ones found on Thingiverse (Ocarina and panpipes. I designed the flute thing just to make sure the design would not be too difficult. I printed them to show the students what can be done, but their instrument should be much simpler than the examples. I was able to play the Ocarina, but the panpipes I do not have the hang of just yet.

Sound is formed by vibrations that travel through the air or another medium. Objectives Design and build a musical instrument that will make at least three different pitches, and use it to create a short song. Skills Learned (Standards) Student will investigate and understand how sound is transmitted.
Key concepts: frequency, waves, wavelength, vibration; the ability of different media to transmit sound;
Students will develop an understanding of engineering design
Students will choose an appropriate measuring device and unit of measure to solve problems involving measurement.
Students will develop on understanding of the role of troubleshooting, research and development, invention and innovation and experimentation in problem solving.

Day 1: Students are introduced to the science of sound and how musical instruments create different pitches.
Day 2: Students are placed in groups and asked to design their own instrument that can be printed. It must play three different pitches of sound, and they should be able to create a tune with it. Students will then use design software (like Tinkercad) to design their instrument.
Day3: Finish creating the design of the instrument and submit for printing.
After the instruments have been printed, students would be given one more class period to develop a song from their instrument.

Depending on the skill level of the students, this lesson should take one class period to discuss the science behind sound, then the students should be given two class periods to design their instruments. Printing time would depend on the number of instruments, size of the instruments, speed and capacity of the printer used.

title: Lulzbot Taz Enclosure LCD + Raspberry Pi + Camera

description.text:
This is a modification of the Lulzbot Taz LCD + Raspberry Pi Case by Scuttlebot. This version allows for a camera to be mounted (Raspberry Pi Camera Mount for 2020 Extrusions by TheOddArtisan) on the side, adjustable with The Popcorn Joint - Simple Ball & Socket Joint for PLA by Wonderbot. It has been successfully tested with a Raspberry Pi 3 running Octoprint (https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=MwsxO3ksxm4).

The lid, enclosure, and camera holder were reverse engineered with Inventor (.ipt) to allow for modifications. The Popcorn Joint can be printed as is, and therefore no .ipt are offered.

The enclosure is well ventilated and provides sufficient holes for connections. It is longer than the original to allow for powering the Pi with microUSB. It is recommended that you print with supports (for the ball joint). Holes can be 'self tapped' with regular screws, but it is recommended to coat screw with lubrication and tap from behind when possible.

The lid has the Colorado flag on it (pictured with white out highlighting this feature, because I was feeling artsy). This is removable in the .ipt. No supports required.

The camera holder was modified to match the Popcorn joints. It is recommended that this be printed with supports. The cable that comes with the camera can be a bit short; longer flex cables to connect the camera can be handy and are inexpensive from Adafruit.

All parts printed with ABS, with normal settings.

Modeling and printing may be purchased. See optogenetic.ucdenver.edu for more information.
